The plaster casts Freeman subsequently made were convincing enough to be considered critical pieces of evidence by anthropologists Jeff Meldrum of Idaho State University and Grover Krantz of Washington State University, who put considerable time and resources into studying them. Others, like René Dahinden and Bob Titmus thought Freeman was simply a hoaxer seeking attention. further_analysis.sub_question: What is the significance of Chris Jones in bluegrass music?
further_analysis.answer: Chris Jones is an American bluegrass singer, guitarist, songwriter, and broadcaster. He fronts the Night Drivers and has significantly contributed to the neo-traditional bluegrass scene. His interest in bluegrass was sparked during his time in Albuquerque, where he lived with his father and stepmother who listened to country and bluegrass. Jones took up guitar at age 12 or 13 and later joined Horse Country as a lead singer and guitarist. His work in bluegrass has been influential, especially in the context of neo-traditional bluegrass, where bands often have more than one lead singer. Jones' contributions to the genre make him a notable figure in bluegrass music history.
